Anonymous Fri 15 Oct 2021 18:44:30 No.42404928 Report
Quoted By: >>42408942
>>42402993
I see this topic often, and I feel like people harp on it too much. I mean, if there were no animal traits present in the anthro beyond looks, yeah, I’d agree, but most of the time, people are making a stink over writers not going far enough. And I say this as a writer, it’s very difficult to balance anthro traits, while keeping the human factor in it, without just using the occasional obvious reference. I make the animalistic traits of my characters subtle, they're more related to their motives rather than obvious stereotypes, and I think that’s what most people miss when talking about this. Because I feel readers expect animalistic traits to the front and center, but my experience in writing has taught me it’s better to integrate them into the character’s thought process and personality.

No, not exactly – we're all xenophiles here (for female anthros, in this context). Hearkening back aways (as it's no longer praxis to my knowledge), if you were around years ago, remember how writers interactively crowdsourced waifur ideas from the general? In some cases, you can see where those writefags were just plugging a fotw species into a pre-fabbed story. When you do that, your species details are an afterthought, beginning with the absolute, universal basics (eg, tail-wagging). Others crowdsourced their waifurs and proceeded to build their settings progressively from there, carefully minding their deets; more elaborate writers planned everything around their species, once chosen, and only plotted their stories thereafter.
